<section class="page-hero">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="breadcrumb">
      <a href="/">Home</a> › CR-1 Spousal Visa
    </div>
    <h1>CR-1 Spousal Visa:<br/>Complete Guide for 2026</h1>
    <p class="hero-desc">Already married to a U.S. citizen or green card holder? The CR-1 is your path to a green card without setting foot in the U.S. first. Here's everything you need to know.</p>
    <div class="hero-meta">
      <span class="hero-meta-item">📅 Updated April 2026</span>
      <span class="hero-meta-item">⏱ 14 min read</span>
      <span class="hero-meta-item">✅ Spouse of U.S. citizen or LPR</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="key-stats">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="kstat"><div class="kstat-num">14–24 mo</div><div class="kstat-label">Avg. total timeline</div></div>
    <div class="kstat"><div class="kstat-num">$1,440</div><div class="kstat-label">Approx. total government fees</div></div>
    <div class="kstat"><div class="kstat-num">3 stages</div><div class="kstat-label">USCIS → NVC → Embassy</div></div>
    <div class="kstat"><div class="kstat-num">2 yrs</div><div class="kstat-label">CR-1 conditional period</div></div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="content-wrap">
  <main class="main-content">

    <section class="section" id="what-is">
      <h2>What Is the CR-1 Spousal Visa?</h2>
      <div class="quick-answer">
        <div class="qa-label">Quick Answer</div>
        <h3>The CR-1 lets a foreign spouse immigrate to the U.S. as a permanent resident — no 90-day deadline, no adjustment of status.</h3>
        <p>Unlike the K-1 (which requires marrying after entry and then adjusting status), the CR-1 is an immigrant visa. You arrive at the U.S. port of entry already as a permanent resident — your green card is mailed to your address within weeks.</p>
      </div>
      <p>The "CR" in CR-1 stands for <strong>Conditional Resident</strong>. It's issued when the marriage is less than 2 years old at the time of visa approval. If your marriage is 2+ years old at approval, you receive an <strong>IR-1</strong> (Immediate Relative) — a 10-year permanent green card with no conditions to remove.</p>
      <p>Both CR-1 and IR-1 are processed through the exact same I-130 petition and NVC pipeline. The type of card you get depends only on how long you've been married when the visa is approved.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="cr1-vs-ir1">
      <h2>CR-1 vs IR-1: What's the Difference?</h2>
      <p>Same process, different outcome based on marriage length at approval time.</p>
      <div class="visa-pair">
        <div class="visa-card cr1">
          <h4>CR-1 — Conditional Resident</h4>
          <p>Marriage less than 2 years old at visa approval</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Green card valid for 2 years</li>
            <li>Must file I-751 within 90 days before expiry</li>
            <li>Joint filing with spouse (or exceptions apply)</li>
            <li>After I-751 approved: 10-year green card</li>
            <li>Can work and travel immediately on arrival</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="visa-card ir1">
          <h4>IR-1 — Immediate Relative</h4>
          <p>Marriage 2+ years old at visa approval</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Green card valid for 10 years</li>
            <li>No removal of conditions needed</li>
            <li>Renewable every 10 years</li>
            <li>Eligible for citizenship in 3 years</li>
            <li>Can work and travel immediately on arrival</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="callout">
        <p><strong>Tip:</strong> If your marriage is close to the 2-year mark, it may be worth waiting until you hit 2 years before filing — you'll arrive with an IR-1 and skip the I-751 process entirely. That said, every month you wait is a month longer before your spouse arrives.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="who-can-apply">
      <h2>Who Can Apply for a CR-1 Visa?</h2>
      <div class="req-grid">
        <div class="req-card">
          <div class="req-icon">💍</div>
          <h4>Legally married</h4>
          <p>The marriage must be legally valid in the country where it took place and recognized under U.S. law. Common-law marriages accepted in some jurisdictions may qualify.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="req-card">
          <div class="req-icon">🇺🇸</div>
          <h4>U.S. citizen or LPR petitioner</h4>
          <p>The petitioner must be a U.S. citizen (no wait) or a lawful permanent resident (F2A category — may involve a wait for a visa number to become available).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="req-card">
          <div class="req-icon">✅</div>
          <h4>Bona fide marriage</h4>
          <p>The marriage must be genuine — entered in good faith, not solely for immigration purposes. USCIS and the consulate both evaluate this.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="req-card">
          <div class="req-icon">💰</div>
          <h4>Income requirement</h4>
          <p>The U.S. petitioner must earn at least 125% of the federal poverty guideline for their household size. In 2026, that's $25,550 for a household of 2.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="req-card">
          <div class="req-icon">📋</div>
          <h4>Prior marriages dissolved</h4>
          <p>Both spouses must be legally free to marry — any prior marriages must be terminated by divorce, annulment, or death of a prior spouse.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="req-card">
          <div class="req-icon">🚫</div>
          <h4>No bars to admissibility</h4>
          <p>The foreign spouse must be admissible to the U.S. — no serious criminal record, immigration violations, or prior fraud that would trigger a ground of inadmissibility.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="process">
      <h2>CR-1 Visa Process: Step by Step</h2>
      <p>Three agencies are involved: USCIS approves the petition, NVC prepares the case, and the U.S. embassy conducts the interview and issues the visa.</p>
      <div class="process-steps">
        <div class="ps">
          <div class="ps-num">1</div>
          <div class="ps-body">
            <h4>File Form I-130 with USCIS</h4>
            <p>The U.S. citizen or LPR spouse files <SmartLink href="/i-130">Form I-130</SmartLink> (Petition for Alien Relative) with supporting documents. This can be filed online at <a href="https://my.uscis.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">my.uscis.gov</a> or by paper mail. Filing fee: $675.</p>
            <span class="ps-time">⏱ 8–14 months processing</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ps">
          <div class="ps-num">2</div>
          <div class="ps-body">
            <h4>USCIS approves the I-130</h4>
            <p>Once approved, USCIS transfers the case to the National Visa Center (NVC). You receive a Notice of Action (I-797) confirming approval and a case number.</p>
            <span class="ps-time">⏱ Included in step 1 timeline</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ps">
          <div class="ps-num">3</div>
          <div class="ps-body">
            <h4>NVC processing &amp; fee payment</h4>
            <p>The NVC assigns a case number and requests immigrant visa fees ($325 visa application fee + $120 Affidavit of Support review fee). Both fees paid online via <a href="https://ceac.state.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ceac.state.gov</a>. The foreign spouse completes the <SmartLink href="/ds-260">DS-260 online visa application</SmartLink> through the CEAC portal. See <SmartLink href="/nvc-processing-time">NVC processing times</SmartLink> for current wait estimates.</p>
            <span class="ps-time">⏱ 2–4 months</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ps">
          <div class="ps-num">4</div>
          <div class="ps-body">
            <h4>NVC completeness check &amp; interview scheduling</h4>
            <p>NVC reviews all documents for completeness (Documentarily Qualified / DQ status). Once DQ, NVC forwards the case to the U.S. embassy in the foreign spouse's country and an interview is scheduled.</p>
            <span class="ps-time">⏱ 1–3 months</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ps">
          <div class="ps-num">5</div>
          <div class="ps-body">
            <h4>Medical exam</h4>
            <p>The foreign spouse completes a medical exam at a USCIS-designated civil surgeon in their home country before or shortly before the interview. The sealed medical envelope is brought to the interview.</p>
            <span class="ps-time">⏱ Schedule 1–2 weeks before interview</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ps">
          <div class="ps-num">6</div>
          <div class="ps-body">
            <h4>Consular interview</h4>
            <p>The foreign spouse attends the interview at the U.S. embassy or consulate. The officer reviews documents and asks questions about the relationship. Most genuine couples are approved on the day. Visa is typically issued within a few days.</p>
            <span class="ps-time">⏱ 30–60 min interview</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ps">
          <div class="ps-num">7</div>
          <div class="ps-body">
            <h4>Visa issued &amp; travel to U.S.</h4>
            <p>After approval, the passport is returned with the immigrant visa stamped inside, plus a sealed immigrant packet. You must enter the U.S. before the visa expiry (typically 6 months). Do not open the sealed packet — the CBP officer at the border will take it.</p>
            <span class="ps-time">⏱ Entry must be within 6 months</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ps">
          <div class="ps-num">8</div>
          <div class="ps-body">
            <h4>Entry &amp; green card mailed</h4>
            <p>At the port of entry, CBP processes your entry as a permanent resident. Your CR-1 or IR-1 green card (Form I-551) is mailed to the U.S. address within 2–4 weeks. You're a permanent resident from the moment of entry.</p>
            <span class="ps-time">⏱ Green card arrives 2–4 weeks</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="costs">
      <h2>CR-1 Visa Costs (2026)</h2>
      <table class="data-table">
