    <section class="section" id="interview">
      <h2>What to Expect at the Consular Interview</h2>
      <p>The consular interview is the most important step. The foreign spouse attends alone (the U.S. citizen typically does not attend). The interviewing officer reviews documents and asks questions about the relationship.</p>
      <h3>Common interview topics</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>How and when you met</li>
        <li>Details about your wedding — date, location, who attended</li>
        <li>Your spouse's daily routine, job, family members</li>
        <li>Where you plan to live in the U.S.</li>
        <li>Future plans together</li>
        <li>How you communicate and how often</li>
        <li>Prior visits to each other's countries</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="warning">
        <p><strong>Prepare together before the interview:</strong> Both spouses should review key facts — wedding date, location, how you met, each other's family members. Inconsistent answers are the #1 red flag. You don't need a perfect memory, but major discrepancies on basic facts can trigger a request for more evidence (221(g) administrative processing).</p>
      </div>
      <h3>What happens after the interview</h3>
      <p>Most cases are approved on the day. Possible outcomes:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Approved:</strong> Passport returned with visa stamped. Sealed immigrant packet provided. Travel to U.S. within 6 months.</li>
        <li><strong>221(g) — administrative processing:</strong> More evidence needed or security checks pending. Common for certain countries. Can take weeks to months.</li>
        <li><strong>Refused:</strong> A specific ground of inadmissibility was found. You'll receive a written notice of the reason. Some refusals can be overcome with waivers.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="after-arrival">
      <h2>After You Arrive in the U.S.</h2>
      <h3>Your first days as a permanent resident</h3>
      <p>When you enter at the port of entry, CBP stamps your passport as proof of permanent resident status. Your physical green card (Form I-551) is mailed to your U.S. address within 2–4 weeks. In the meantime, your passport stamp serves as temporary proof of status.</p>
      <h3>What you can do immediately</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Apply for a Social Security Number (SSN) — visit your local SSA office with your passport and entry stamp</li>
        <li>Get a state driver's license or ID</li>
        <li>Open a U.S. bank account</li>
        <li>Work for any U.S. employer (no separate work permit needed)</li>
        <li>Travel internationally (with your green card)</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>If you received a CR-1 (conditional green card)</h3>
      <p>Your green card expires 2 years after your entry. <strong>Within the 90-day window before expiry</strong>, you must file Form I-751 (Petition to Remove Conditions on Residence) jointly with your spouse. Filing I-751 extends your status automatically while it's pending. Approval converts your CR-1 to a 10-year permanent green card. For a full overview of how the CR-1 fits into the broader path to permanent residency, see the <SmartLink href="/green-card-through-marriage">green card through marriage guide</SmartLink>. Not yet married? The <SmartLink href="/k1-visa">K-1 fiancé visa</SmartLink> is an alternative path for couples who haven't wed yet.</p>
      <div class="warning">
        <p><strong>Don't miss the I-751 window:</strong> You must file within the 90 days before your CR-1 expires — not before, not after. Filing late requires a written explanation and may cause problems. Mark the date in your calendar when you receive your green card.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="faq">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is the difference between CR-1 and IR-1?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">CR-1 (Conditional Resident) is for marriages under 2 years old at visa approval — you get a 2-year green card. IR-1 (Immediate Relative) is for marriages 2+ years old — you get a 10-year green card with no conditions. Both use the same I-130 process.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How long does the CR-1 visa take in 2026?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Typically 14–24 months total: 8–14 months for USCIS to approve the I-130, 2–4 months for NVC processing, and 1–3 months for the consular appointment. Times vary significantly by country and USCIS service center.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Can a green card holder file for a CR-1?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes, but spouses of LPRs (F2A category) must wait for a visa number, which can add significant time. Spouses of U.S. citizens are immediate relatives with no numerical limit and no visa wait.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Is the CR-1 faster than the K-1?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">It depends on the situation. The K-1 is often faster to get your partner into the U.S., but the CR-1 skips the adjustment of status process after arrival (saving 12–24 months and ~$1,440). For couples who are already married, the CR-1 is usually the better long-term choice. See our <SmartLink href="/k1-vs-cr1">K-1 vs CR-1 full comparison</SmartLink>.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Do I need an immigration attorney for the CR-1?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Not required. Many couples complete the CR-1 process without an attorney. If your situation is straightforward (valid marriage, clean background, no prior immigration issues), DIY is very manageable. An attorney adds value when there are complications like prior visa denials, criminal history, or prior overstays.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is the income requirement for the CR-1 visa?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The U.S. petitioner must earn at least 125% of the federal poverty guideline for their household size. For a household of 2 in 2026, that's $25,550/year. If the petitioner doesn't meet this, a joint sponsor can co-sign the I-864. See our <SmartLink href="/affidavit-of-support">Affidavit of Support guide</SmartLink>.</div>
      </div>
    </section>

